# Conditional Statements in Java

Every useful program makes decisions. Think of an ATM: it checks your PIN, then checks your balance before dispensing cash. An `if` statement lets your Java program do the same — run a block of code only when a specific condition is true.

## The if Statement

```java
int temperature = 38;
if (temperature > 37) {
    System.out.println("You have a fever.");
}
```

Two essential rules:
1. The condition goes inside **parentheses** `()`
2. The body goes inside **curly braces** `{}`

Unlike Python, Java uses braces rather than indentation to define blocks.

## Adding else

```java
if (temperature > 37) {
    System.out.println("Fever detected.");
} else {
    System.out.println("Temperature is normal.");
}
```

The `else` block runs when the `if` condition is `false`. It has no condition of its own.

## Multiple Conditions with else if

```java
int score = 75;

if (score >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Grade: A");
} else if (score >= 80) {
    System.out.println("Grade: B");
} else if (score >= 70) {
    System.out.println("Grade: C");
} else {
    System.out.println("Grade: F");
}
```

Java evaluates conditions top to bottom and executes only the first block whose condition is `true`. All remaining branches are skipped.

## The Ternary Operator

For simple two-outcome decisions, the ternary operator provides a one-line shortcut:

```java
String status = score >= 50 ? "Pass" : "Fail";
```

This is equivalent to:
```java
String status;
if (score >= 50) { status = "Pass"; }
else             { status = "Fail"; }
```

## Nested if Statements

An `if` block can contain another `if` block. Keep nesting depth to two levels maximum to maintain readability:

```java
if (hasAccount) {
    if (balance >= amount) {
        System.out.println("Transaction approved.");
    } else {
        System.out.println("Insufficient funds.");
    }
}
```

In the code example below, you will see a complete grade classifier using all branching forms.

codeExample.code:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String studentName = "Sneha Patel";
        int    score       = 83;

        // Multi-branch grade assignment
        String grade, feedback;

        if (score >= 90) {
            grade    = "A";
            feedback = "Outstanding performance!";
        } else if (score >= 80) {
            grade    = "B";
            feedback = "Great work, keep it up!";
        } else if (score >= 70) {
            grade    = "C";
            feedback = "Good effort, room to improve.";
        } else if (score >= 60) {
            grade    = "D";
            feedback = "Needs more practice.";
        } else {
            grade    = "F";
            feedback = "Please seek extra help.";
        }

        System.out.println("Student  : " + studentName);
        System.out.println("Score    : " + score + "/100");
        System.out.println("Grade    : " + grade);
        System.out.println("Feedback : " + feedback);

        // Ternary operator
        String result = score >= 50 ? "PASS" : "FAIL";
        System.out.println("Result   : " + result);
    }
}

