# The switch Statement

When you need to compare one variable against many specific values, a long `if/else if` chain becomes hard to read. The `switch` statement provides a cleaner alternative for matching a single expression against a fixed list of values.

## Classic switch Syntax

```java
switch (expression) {
    case value1:
        // code
        break;
    case value2:
        // code
        break;
    default:
        // code for no match
}
```

The `expression` is evaluated once. Java jumps to the matching `case` label and executes code until it hits a `break`. Without `break`, execution **falls through** to the next case.

## Supported Types

The `switch` expression can be: `int`, `byte`, `short`, `char`, `String`, or an enum. It cannot be `long`, `double`, or `boolean`.

## Fall-Through — Intentional and Accidental

```java
int day = 3;
switch (day) {
    case 1:
    case 2:
    case 3:
    case 4:
    case 5:
        System.out.println("Weekday");  // all 5 cases share this
        break;
    case 6:
    case 7:
        System.out.println("Weekend");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Invalid day");
}
```

Grouping cases this way is intentional fall-through — useful when multiple values should produce the same result.

## Switch Expressions (Java 14+)

Java 14 introduced enhanced switch expressions with arrow syntax — cleaner and safer:

```java
String dayName = switch (day) {
    case 1 -> "Monday";
    case 2 -> "Tuesday";
    case 6, 7 -> "Weekend";    // multiple values per arrow case
    default  -> "Unknown";
};
```

Arrow cases do not fall through and do not require `break`. They produce a value that can be assigned directly.

## switch vs if/else if

Use `switch` when:
- Comparing one variable against specific literal values
- You have 4 or more branches
- All conditions test the same variable

Use `if/else if` when:
- Conditions involve ranges (`score >= 90`)
- Different variables are tested in different branches

In the code example below, you will see both classic and enhanced switch handling a course plan selection.

codeExample.code:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String plan = "pro";

        // Classic switch with fall-through grouping
        System.out.println("=== Classic switch ===");
        switch (plan) {
            case "bundle":
                System.out.println("All 4 languages");
                System.out.println("Offline mode");
                // falls through to pro features
            case "pro":
                System.out.println("AI mentor hints");
                System.out.println("Progress tracker");
                break;
            case "starter":
                System.out.println("1 language");
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Python only (free)");
        }

        // Switch expression (Java 14+)
        System.out.println("\n=== Switch expression ===");
        int courseCount = switch (plan) {
            case "bundle" -> 4;
            case "pro"    -> 2;
            case "starter"-> 1;
            default       -> 0;
        };
        System.out.println("Courses in plan: " + courseCount);

        // Switch on char
        char grade = 'B';
        String feedback = switch (grade) {
            case 'A' -> "Outstanding!";
            case 'B' -> "Well done!";
            case 'C' -> "Keep practising.";
            default  -> "Seek guidance.";
        };
        System.out.println("Feedback: " + feedback);
    }
}

